orm of English   Harwood  ."]},{"name":"Arwood","meanings":["English: variant of   Harwood  ."]},{"name":"Harewood","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Harwood  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Wharwood was born in 1480, in England, United Kingdom, her father, John Whorwood, was 19 and her mother, Margaret Fowke, was 16. She married Roger Fowke in 1509, in Brewood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 24 January 1561, in Brewood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 81, and was buried in Brewood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1480–24 January 1561":"1480–24. jaanuar 1561","1480–1561":"1480–1561","1486–1527":"1486–1527","1505–Female":"1505–Surnud","1494–1544":"1494–1544","1530–1558":"1530–1558","1461–1516":"1461–1516","1464–1490":"1464–1490","1561":"1561","1461":"1461","1494":"1494","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","18 February 1558":"18. veebruar 1558","1558":"1558","1544":"1544","1530":"1530","1464":"1464","1486":"1486","1509":"1509","10 March 1544":"10. märts 1544","1516":"1516","1505":"1505","1527":"1527","24 January 1561":"24. jaanuar 1561","Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England":"Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brewood, Staffordshire, Kingdom of England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",", , , England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1480–24 January 1561":"1480–24. tammikuuta 1561","1480–1561":"1480–1561","1486–1527":"1486–1527","1505–Female":"1505–Kuollut","1494–1544":"1494–1544","1530–1558":"1530–1558","1461–1516":"14